76561198007300752,Not Recommended,288140,22818541,"Posted: 5 May, 2016",all,Blackadar,"EDIT: Review changed in 9/16 to reflect a lack of progress in providing features that were supposed to be in the release. Specifically, the course designer for PG has been long discussed and was supposed to be in the game on release. 4 months later it's still not there. Beyond the course designer, there still is no career mode. The game still has performance issues. There still is limited character customization, no announcers, very limited stats, poor UI, etc. Essentially almost NONE of the negatives have been fixed even though many of those things have been promised. Thus I can't recommend the game because I don't see tangible progress in improving the product.-----I've been arounds since PG's failed kickstarter. I bought the game as soon as it came out on Early Access. However, that doesn't make me a fan. It makes me a fan of golf games. PG does some things right. It does some things wrong. Because it's a mixed bag, it's easier to list what is good and what's bad about it. As always, YMMV.Pros:- numerous swing type options - there are multiple though I'm a three clicker all the way and very impressed by the smoothness of the meter. The mouse swing is challenging. They've tried to implement no-cheating modes but they broke the mouse swing while doing so.- various levels of challenge - play this with all the aids on and you'll be in birdie city. Play this without them and you might be lucky to break 90. I'm not nearly as good as I once was, but at one point I was in the top 10 on Case's Ladder on Links and #1 on another ladder. So I'm glad it's challenging rather than the ""Shoot 48 at Augusta on Tiger Woods"" mode.- good physics - I'm still not happy with the backspin but generally the physics are good and better than any other golf game. Backspin still is off and I generate more backspin on my short irons (and I shoot in the 90s) than my avatar in this game. Other than that they're spot on. For instance, if you play a course at higher elevation the ball will travel further. That's a nice touch.- weather / time of day settings can add some real challenge to your game. I think the wind feels spot-on.- many different courses to choose from and quite a few to download- multiple modes of gameplay, including solo, multiplayer and tournaments with match play, team play, alt shot, etc.- no micro-transactions that improve your game- no stupid characters that drive the ball 400 yards. Over-driving distance ruins so many golf games and they've prevented that here.Cons:- no career mode built into the game yet- course designer hasn't been released yet (it's now 4 months late and counting)- I don't like the way the skies look and the trees can look a little jagged- limited current player animations (no lefties, no females yet though they're coming)- very,very, very limited character customization- it requires a decent computer and user made courses don't always run well. In fact, the user made courses often exceed the RAM allowance in the game causing major problems from a chunky swing meter to crashing.- slightly too limited shot shaping options. I wish I could position my swing path and feet differently to get inventive when shotmaking.- very limited stats- no announcer and limited sound effects- no Steam Workshop integration (a cardinal sin for a game with downloadable courses)- really poor and frankly butt-ugly user interface when you enter the game (though it's fine when actually playing a round)So it's up to you whether to buy it. I can tell you it's a better game than that ""other"" golf game on Steam and probably the best one available on the market today. But it's by no means perfect yet (pun intended) and while I had hoped that many of the cons would be fixed, this doesn't seem to be happening. The product feels more and more abandoned with a lack of substantial progress since release.If you want a golf game now, this is the one to buy becuase frankly it's probably your only decent choice. Since I'm a fan of the old Links games and golf games in general so I continue to load up PG from time to time. But if you aren't a golf nut, this game isn't for you because it's just too limited in the features and progress to appeal to a wider audience."
