76561198109536056,Recommended,288140,31662604,Posted: 10 May,all,uncle_adolph,"First, the good points. If you simply want to play a round of computer golf that looks and feels reasonably realistic and where you feel that the results are down to your own skill rather than pure luck then this will suit you. Using the motion swing control method it will take an awful lot of practice to hit the ball accurately particularly when it comes to putting. After more than 40 hours playing I am still to complete a round anything better than +5.....But unfortunately the game has a totally unfinished air to it. There is no career mode and, worse of all, no player stats within the game. I find it totally incomprehensible that in a game that stats were created for there is simply nothing. And that brings up the other big problem....no feedback and no support. Very, very disappointing.The game does come with a number of courses both real and fantasy which are generally very good. There is also a website where further courses can be downloaded. But that, in itself, brings another problem....the PP servers are currently down and when they are (which is rather frequently) then the downloaded courses don't show in the game and can't be played. Aaaargh!I would love to recommend this game but in all honesty, regrettably, I can't. Sorry!Review Mk 2:After more weeks of playing the game, and whilst I still bemoan the lack of a career mode or readily accessible stats, I have to slightly revise my review.Whilst I didn't mention it above one of the things I disliked about the game was the infamous ""lip out"" with putting and the devs have now greatly improved that. And whilst I'm still hopeless at the game (I still haven't done a round in anything better than +2) perhaps it does more reflect real ability than pure luck.So if you can accept the drawbacks I will give it cautious approval!"
